Spheres of influence in 1900 
In the early 1600s, the Dutch attempted to take this valuable transpacific route away from the Spanish, but were unsuccessful.
Spain controlled this transpacific trade route between the Philippines and Mexico for almost three centuries. 
Spain's colonization of the Americas as well as the Western Pacific led to the development of an early trans-pacific trade route.
The USA did not enter the Pacific Basin until the early 19th century, initially to engage in whaling and trade with China.
The French and the British agreed that the Nile and Congo rivers would mark the frontier between their spheres of influence.
